I&#39;m gonna go ahead and assume that your own code confuses you and adding another layer of the same would make the code unreadable.  
To fix this, we can introduce a function that checks whether a number is a palindrome.

```c++
bool is_palindrome(const int num){
	int reversed_num = 0;
	int temp = num;

	while(temp){
		int last_num = temp % 10;
		temp /= 10;

		reversed_num = reversed_num * 10 + last_num;
	}

	return num == reversed_num;
}
```
We can also make this function much more readable by using `std::string`.
```c++
bool is_palindrome(const int num){
	string original = to_string(num);

	return original == string(rbegin(original), rend(original));
}
```
In the latter, we use reverse `begin` and `end` iterators to construct the same, but reversed string.

Now, your code looks much cleaner and more readable.

```c++
int main(){
	for(int num = 0; num &lt;= 1000; ++num){
		if(is_palindrome(num) &amp;&amp; is_palindrome(num * num)){
			cout &lt;&lt; num &lt;&lt; &#39;\n&#39;;
		}
	}

	return 0;
}
```

